ference B and reasoning. We need to consider all candidates.\n\nWe have our own knowledge (the full list). Let's list all attributes again:\n\nA: anticipate dangerous situations; see complex connections; excellent spatial vision; very good leadership qualities; regarded as a show-off; regarded as not open to new ideas.\n\nB: very conscientious; handles stress very well; good at assessing weather conditions; excellent computer skills; relatively weak memory for numbers; makes nasty remarks about his colleagues.\n\nC: can make correct decisions quickly; difficulty communicating ideas; regarded as egocentric; not very willing to further his education; keeps calm in a crisis; understands complicated technology.\n\nD: responds to unexpected events adequately; can concentrate very well; solves problems extremely well; takes responsibility seriously; regarded as a know-it-all; has a hot temper.\n\nWe also have extra info from Agent 1: A has no info on reliability, stress handling, teamwork. Also A is unfriendly, eats unhealthily (but not relevant). B is regarded as pretentious, sometimes adopts wrong tone when communicating (additional teamwork issues). B also has the earlier info. C puts concern for others above everything, has excellent attention skills. D is considered moody, regarded as a loner.\n\nWe need to weigh for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nLet's evaluate each candidate with all info:\n\nCandidate A:\n- Strengths: anticipates dangerous situations (risk awareness), sees complex connections (systems thinking), excellent spatial vision (navigation), very good leadership qualities (crew management). Weaknesses: regarded as show-off, not open to new ideas (rigidity), unfriendly, eats unhealthily (maybe health concerns). No explicit reliability, stress handling, teamwork info. Leadership suggests some teamwork, but show-off/unfriendly may hinder. Unorganized? Not mentioned here. So uncertain.\n\nCandidate B:\n- Strengths: very conscientious (reliability), handles stress well (calm under pressure), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (tech). Weaknesses: relatively weak memory for numbers (could affect calculations), makes nasty remarks, regarded as pretentious, sometimes wrong tone (teamwork issues). So reliability high, stress handling high, but teamwork poor.\n\nCandidate C:\n- Strengths: can make correct decisions quickly (decision-making), keeps calm in crisis (stress handling), understands complicated technology (technical), puts concern for others above everything (teamwork/crew care), excellent attention skills (focus). Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education (development). So reliability? Not explicit, but concern for others suggests reliability. Teamwork mixed: caring but communication difficulty and egocentric. Professional development limited.\n\nCandidate D:\n- Strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately (adaptability), can concentrate very well (focus), solves problems extremely well (technical), takes responsibility seriously (reliability), has hot temper (neg), regarded as know-it-all (arrogance), moody, loner (teamwork issues). So reliability decent, but teamwork poor, stress handling uncertain (hot temper). Professional development? Not indicated.\n\nThus best overall may be B (reliability, stress, technical) but teamwork issues. C also strong in stress, decision, caring, but communication issues and lack of development. D strong problem solving but temperament issues. A strong anticipation and leadership but unknown reliability and stress.\n\nGiven the importance of teamwork and communication for long flights, B's negative behavior could be serious. C's caring and calm may offset communication difficulty? But egocentric and unwilling to learn is concerning for long-term.\n\nWe need to state provisional preference, maybe still B but note uncertainty about teamwork. Or maybe C? Let's weigh: reliability: B high, C moderate, D high, A unknown. Stress handling: B high, C high, D unknown (hot temper), A unknown. Technical: B good weather/computer, C tech understanding, D problem solving, A spatial vision. Decision-making: A anticipates, C quick decisions, D problem solving, B weather assessment. Teamwork: C caring but communication difficulty, B poor, D poor, A unknown but leadership maybe good but show-off.\n\nOverall, B's teamwork issues may be mitigated by training, but long-distance flights require crew harmony. C's communication difficulty could be more severe. I think B still best overall, but we need to note that if teamwork issues are severe, could shift to C or D.\n\nThus provisional vote: Candidate B.\n\nWe must include evidence from our own knowledge and from others: Agent 1's info on B reliability and teamwork, Agent 2's provisional vote B, and other candidate info.\n\nWe also need to state remaining uncertainty: lack of concrete data on A's reliability and stress, D's stress handling, C's reliability, etc. Also unknown how B's negative remarks affect actual crew performance.\n\nWhat would change vote: positive teamwork evidence for B, or strong teamwork for another candidate, or evidence of reliability issues for B.\n\nNow produce output."}
